{"title": "You can't bury them all: Poems", "price": "33.63", "rating": 2, "upc": "55f9da0c5eea2e10", "product_type": "Books", "price_exclude_tax": "33.63", "price_include_tax": "33.63", "tax": "0.00", "availability": "17", "number_of_reviews": "0", "description": "A poetry that is at once harrowing, angry, and achingly beautiful Patrick Woodcock has spent the past seven years engaging with and being shaped by the people, politics, and landscapes of the Kurdish north of Iraq, Fort Good Hope in the Northwest Territories, and Azerbaijan. His powerful new collection offers a poetry that simultaneously explores hope and horror while doc A poetry that is at once harrowing, angry, and achingly beautiful Patrick Woodcock has spent the past seven years engaging with and being shaped by the people, politics, and landscapes of the Kurdish north of Iraq, Fort Good Hope in the Northwest Territories, and Azerbaijan. His powerful new collection offers a poetry that simultaneously explores hope and horror while documenting the transformative processes of coping. You can\u00e2\u0080\u0099t bury them all follows the narratives we construct to survive the tragic failures of our humanity to their very end: everything that\u00e2\u0080\u0099s buried by snow, dirt, and ash, just like everything that\u00e2\u0080\u0099s buried by politics, homophobia, sexism, racism, religion; and history is resurrected, demanding to be heard and addressed.In Woodcock\u00e2\u0080\u0099s poetry, how we deal with what resurfaces is the key. What do those who suffer really mean to those who have abandoned them to small, conscience-soothing charitable donations or the occasional tweet? How can the poet, or anyone else, sleep at night knowing homosexuals are being thrown off building tops, after one steps into a hole and finds an abandoned corpse in an Azeri cemetery, or after the elders of an Aboriginal community are left helpless against those who only want to exploit them? Still, You can\u00e2\u0080\u0099t bury them all demonstrates that the world is not just the horrific place the media often portrays. In each of the worlds he touches, Woodcock discovers a spirit and strength to celebrate. ...more", "image_url": "https://books.toscrape.com/media/cache/b7/44/b7440aa88046b0bf8cba50d59295518e.jpg", "image_path": "images/"}
